39    /**
40    * Factory that creates complex instances of DateTimeFormatter via method calls.
41    * <p>
42    * Datetime formatting is performed by the {@link DateTimeFormatter} class.
43    * Three classes provide factory methods to create formatters, and this is one.
44    * The others are {@link DateTimeFormat} and {@link ISODateTimeFormat}.
45    * <p>
46    * DateTimeFormatterBuilder is used for constructing formatters which are then
47    * used to print or parse. The formatters are built by appending specific fields
48    * or other formatters to an instance of this builder.
49    * <p>
50    * For example, a formatter that prints month and year, like "January 1970",
51    * can be constructed as follows:
52    * <p>
53    * <pre>
54    * DateTimeFormatter monthAndYear = new DateTimeFormatterBuilder()
55    * .appendMonthOfYearText()
56    * .appendLiteral(' ')
57    * .appendYear(4, 4)
58    * .toFormatter();
59    * </pre>
60    * <p>
61    * DateTimeFormatterBuilder itself is mutable and not thread-safe, but the
62    * formatters that it builds are thread-safe and immutable.
63    *
64    * @author Brian S O'Neill
65    * @author Stephen Colebourne
66    * @author Fredrik Borgh
67    * @see DateTimeFormat
68    * @see ISODateTimeFormat
69    * @since 1.0
70    */

291    /**
292    * Appends a printer and a set of matching parsers. When parsing, the first
293    * parser in the list is selected for parsing. If it fails, the next is
294    * chosen, and so on. If none of these parsers succeeds, then the failed
295    * position of the parser that made the greatest progress is returned.
296    * <p>
297    * Only the printer is optional. In addition, it is illegal for any but the
298    * last of the parser array elements to be null. If the last element is
299    * null, this represents the empty parser. The presence of an empty parser
300    * indicates that the entire array of parse formats is optional.
301    * <p>
302    * The printer and parser interfaces are the low-level part of the formatting API.
303    * Normally, instances are extracted from another formatter.
304    * Note however that any formatter specific information, such as the locale,
305    * time-zone, chronology, offset parsing or pivot/default year, will not be
306    * extracted by this method.
307    *
308    * @param printer the printer to add

313    */
